ng Acids','What is the principle characteristic of strong acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,61,4),(519,'Incorrect','There are only a few strong acids in water. You should be able to recognize these acids.\n\nStrong acids include hydrochloric acid, hydrobromic acid, hydroiodic acid, chloric acid, perchloric acid, nitric acid, and sulfuric acid (first ionization only).',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,60,5),(520,'Incorrect','STRONG acids are characterized by COMPLETE dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.\n\nWEAK acids are characterized by PARTIAL dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,6),(521,'Incorrect','Acids are characterized by their dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counterion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,7),(522,'Concentration of Hydronium','Given that HCl completely dissociates in water to form hydronium and chloride, what will be the concentration of hydronium in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,62,8),(523,'Concentration of Chloride','What will be the concentration of chloride in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,63,9),(524,'Incorrect','The concentration of hydronium and chloride are related to the initial concentration of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,10),(525,'pH of 0.010 M Hydrochloric Acid','The pH of 0.010 M HCl (aq) is calculated as shown, yielding a result of pH 2.\n\nThis result can be also be obtained from a systematic equations approach. Although unnecessary for strong acids, an systematic equations approach will prove useful later, so we’ll apply it to HCl (aq) first.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,77,11),(526,'Systematic Equations Approach','The systematic approach has three bases: (1) equilibrium constant equation(s); (2) mass balance equation(s); and (3) a charge balance equation.\n\nCan an equilibrium constant equation be written for HCl (aq) or any other strong acid in water?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,61,12),(527,'Incorrect','Strong acids completely dissociate and do not have an equilibrium constant associated with that dissociation (i.e., Ka is not defined because the equilibrium lies too far in favour of the product ions). \n\nTherefore, an equilibrium constant equation cannot be written.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,13),(528,'Mass Balance Equation','Mass balance equations keep track of the conservation of matter. No matter how an acid or base dissociates, the amounts of the conjugate species must add up to the amount originally added.\n\nComplete the mass balance (M.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq) by filling in the blank.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,65,14),(529,'Yes, but...','You\'re not wrong; however, you only know the concentration of hydronium because of your intuitive knowledge of strong acid behaviour.\n\nIf a weak acid were considered, or if there was another acidic or basic species in solution, you would not immediately know the concentration of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,66,15),(530,'Think Counter-Ion','The chloride counter-ion is neither an acid nor a base. We can therefore always know its concentration from the amount of HCl (or other chloride-containing salts) added to solution.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,66,16),(531,'Incorrect','Imagine that you have 6 pens with lids. If you take the lid off each pen (i.e., \"dissociate\" the pen), do you have 6 pen bodies and 6 pen lids? \n\nIf you start with 6 HCl molecules, do you get 6 hydronium and 6 chloride ions?\n\nYour equation does not yield the result you would expect given the above.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,17),(532,'Charge Balance Equation','The charge balance equation (there is only one) keeps track of the total charge of the solution, which must be neutral. The concentration of positive charge must therefore match the concentration of negative charge.\n\nChoose the correct charge balance (M.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq).',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,61,18),(533,'pH of 0.010 M HCl Completed','The set of systematic equations is shown for HCl (aq). One can immediately arrive at the answer of [H3O+] = 0.010 M, which corresponds to pH 2.\n\nAgain, the systematic approach is not strictly needed for a solution of strong acid. Nonetheless, it mirrors the intuitive process of solving the problem.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,67,19),(534,'Incorrect','To write a C.B. equation, sum the positive charge and negative charge on opposite sides of the equation. Each ion contributes a total charge equal to its concentration multiplied by the charge per ion.\n\nThe C.B. equation does not include the initial concentrations of acids and bases.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,20),(535,'What is acetic acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,68,21),(536,'Weak Acids','What is the principle characteristic of weak acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,61,22),(537,'Acetic Acid is a Weak Acid','We will now calculate the pH of a 0.10 M aqueous solution of acetic acid using the systematic equations approach.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,69,23),(538,'Equilibrium Constant Equation','Which of the above is the correct equilibrium equation corresponding to the acid dissociation constant, Ka.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,70,24),(539,'Incorrect','The equilibrium constant equation is products over reactants.\n\nWhen water is the solvent, it does not enter in the equilibrium constant equation because its concentration is very large and thus effectively constant.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,25),(540,'Mass Balance Equation','What terms complete the right hand side of the mass balance equation for 0.10 M acetic acid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,71,26),(541,'Incorrect','A mass balance equation of 0.10 M = [CH3COO–] would only be true if acetic acid were a strong acid.\n\nAcetic acid is a weak acid, so a significant amount of undissociated CH3COOH will remain.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,27),(542,'Incorrect','Hydronium is derived from water, which is in huge excess relative to any added acid or base. Mass balance equations with hydronium and, similarly, hydroxide, cannot usually be written.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,28),(543,'Incorrect','Hydronium is derived from water, which is in huge excess relative to any added acid or base. Mass balance equations with hydronium and, similarly, hydroxide, cannot usually be written.\n\nIn addition, acetic acid is a weak acid, so a significant amount of undissociated CH3COOH will remain.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,29),(544,'Charge Balance Equation','Choose the correct charge balance equation.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,72,30),(545,'System of Equations for Acetic Acid','These equations comprise a complete system for determining the concentration of hydronium (or any other species) in a 0.10 M aqueous solution of acetic acid.\n\nNote that the equation for the autoionization water was added. This equation is always applicable in water.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,74,31),(546,'Incorrect','The charge balance equation should contain no uncharged species, and total negative charge must equal the total positive charge.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,NULL,32),(547,'Systematic Equations: Algebra','The M.B. equation can be substituted into the Ka equation to yield an expression for acetate in terms of hydronium. This new equation can be substituted into the C.B. equation along with the Kw equation. The result is a quadratic equation for hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,74,33),(548,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','The mathematics can be simplified by making assumptions based on  knowledge of the chemistry of the system.\n\nGiven that a solution of acetic acid will be acetic, what assumption can be made?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,74,34),(549,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','With the assumption of an acidic solution, the C.B. equation simplifies as shown.\n\nGiven that acetic acid is a weak acid, and that its initial concentration is larger than its Ka value, what further assumption can be made in the M.B. equation?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,75,35),(550,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','With these two assumptions, the system of equations is simplified as shown. The mathematical solution is more readily obtained than it is without the assumptions.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,76,36),(551,'pH of 0.10 M Acetic Acid','The calculated pH without approximations is  2.87.\n\nThe calculated pH with approximations is 2.87. (The difference is in non-significant digits.)\n\nThe error introduced by the approximation is generally considered acceptable if less than 5%. In this case, the error would be < 1%.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,78,37),(552,'Mixture of Acetic Acid and Hydrochloric Acid','The systematic equations approach will now be applied to a mixture of 0.10 M acetic acid and 0.010 M hydrochloric acid. \n\nAssumptions will then be made if possible.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,79,38),(553,'Incorrect','When dissolving only acid, it can be assumed that the final solution will be acidic. In this case, the concentration o