ically.',1,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,56,1),(582,'Scenario',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,57,2),(583,'What is hydrochloric acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,59,3),(584,'Strong Acids','What is the principle characteristic of strong acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,61,4),(585,'Incorrect','There are only a few strong acids in water. You should be able to recognize these acids.\n\nStrong acids include hydrochloric acid, hydrobromic acid, hydroiodic acid, chloric acid, perchloric acid, nitric acid, and sulfuric acid (first ionization only).',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,60,5),(586,'Incorrect','STRONG acids are characterized by COMPLETE dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.\n\nWEAK acids are characterized by PARTIAL dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,6),(587,'Incorrect','Acids are characterized by their dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counterion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,7),(588,'Concentration of Hydronium','Given that HCl completely dissociates in water to form hydronium and chloride, what will be the concentration of hydronium in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,62,8),(589,'Concentration of Chloride','What will be the concentration of chloride in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,63,9),(590,'Incorrect','The concentration of hydronium and chloride are related to the initial concentration of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,10),(591,'pH of 0.010 M Hydrochloric Acid','The pH of 0.010 M HCl (aq) is calculated as shown, yielding a result of pH 2.\n\nThis result can be also be obtained from a systematic equations approach. Although unnecessary for strong acids,