ct','Water is a very weak acid. It may contribute to the observed pH in very dilute solutions of acid or base, but normally will exert little if any effect when an strong/weak acid or base is present.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,45),(626,'Incorrect','Since HCl is a strong acid, it does not have an associated equilibrium equation. There is only the equilibrium equation for acetic acid.\n\nThe charge balance equation ensures the net charge of the solution is zero. Since there is only one solution, there is only one charge balance equation.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,46),(627,'Incorrect','Since HCl is a strong acid, it does not have an associated equilibrium equation. There is only the equilibrium equation for acetic acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,47),(628,'Incorrect','The charge balance equation ensures the net charge of the solution is zero. Since there is only one solution, there is only one charge balance equation.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,48),(629,'Incorrect','There are two acids that dissociate (albeit to different degrees). Two mass balance equations are therefore required to keep track of the non-hydronium species.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,49),(630,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','You have correctly identified the number of equations required to systematically determine the pH of the mixture.\n\nIs the equilibrium equation for the acetic acid in the mixture with hydrochloric acid any different than for acetic acid alone?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,84,50),(631,'Incorrect','Equilibrium equations are invariant. The presence of additional equilibrium reactions or species does not affect the equilibrium equation for the dissociation of acetic acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,51),(632,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Which of the equations shown is the correct charge balance equation for a mixture of hydrochloric acid and acetic acid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,82,52),(633,'Incorrect','Remember that the charge balance equation balances all of the charges in the entire solution. This equation must therefore include ions from both the dissociation of acetic acid and from the dissociation of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,53),(634,'Incorrect','There is only one concentration of hydronium in a solution regardless of the acid source. There is no need to count its concentration twice just because there are two acids in solution.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,54),(635,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The charge balance equation for the mixture must include both the chloride and acetate counter-ions, plus the usual hydronium and hydroxide.\n\nAre the two mass balance equations for the mixture any different than the mass balance equations for hydrochloric acid and acetic acid separately?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,86,55),(636,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The equilibrium expression for the dissociation of acetic acid is unchanged.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,85,56),(637,'Incorrect','Hydronium notwithstanding, the hydrochloric acid and acetic acid to produce the same ions in solution. The mass balance equations are therefore unchanged.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,57),(638,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. We now have a complete set of equations for the mixture of 0.10 M acetic acid and 0.010 M hydrochloric acid.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,87,58),(639,'Sytematic Equations: Assumptions','What assumptions can make to simplify the solution to this system of equations?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,87,59),(640,'A Potentially Good Assumption','If you assume that [CH3COO-] << [Cl-], then you have assumed that the acetic acid does not contribute to the pH of the solution of 0.010 M hydrochloric acid and 0.10 M acetic acid.\n\nThis may or may not be the case. For the moment, let\'s assume its not a valid assumption and continue.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,66,60),(641,'Simplified System of Equations','With the assumptions that [OH-] and the dissociation of acetic acid are negligible, the equations simplify as shown above. \n\nThe equations can be algebraically reduced to a quadratic equation in terms of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,89,61),(642,'Solving the Simplified Equation','The calculated pH is 1.99. \n\nIf we had assumed the acetic acid had no effect on the pH with hydrochloric acid present, the calculated pH would have been 2.00. Thus, such as assumption would have been acceptable.\n\nWhen would this assumption become less likely to be valid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,90,62),(643,'Incorrect','Both the concentration of hydrochloric acid relative to the acetic acid and the strength of the weak acid will affect the contribution of the weak acid to the overall solution pH.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,63),(644,'Correct. Both the concentration of strong acid and strength of the weak acid are important.','With 0.0010 M HCl (aq) and 0.10 M CH3OOH (aq), the pH would 2.71 (vs. 3.00 for HCl alone). \n\nWith Ka = 1.8E-3 for 0.10 M weak acid (vs. 1.8E-5 for acetic acid) the pH with 0.010 M HCl (aq) would be 1.71 (vs. 1.99 in the current acetic acid mixture).',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,66,64),(645,'Success!','Congratulations! You have complete this scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,55,65),(646,'Incorrect','If 0.10 M acetic acid had minimal effect on the pH when mixed with 0.010 M hydrochloric acid, then a weak acid with a smaller dissociation constant will have even less effect (i.e., virtually none).',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,66);
